@@eThe Knight Tradition@@N

@@yThe Iron Reformation@@N
Knights are the formalized inheritors of the warden tradition, born from the Iron
Reformation that followed the Ninth Meridian Catastrophe. Eastern campaign warlords
found that their warden resources, however skilled individually, repeatedly failed
at siege operations requiring sustained coordination. The Compact of the Seven
Chains established mutual rules of engagement and created a new officer class whose
primary institutional loyalty was to a shared doctrine rather than to any employer.

@@yFormation Superiority@@N
The foundational Knight doctrine holds that controlled aggression within a
disciplined structure reliably defeats individual excellence without structure. The
training was deliberately extended: recruits underwent years of weapon drill not
because the physical techniques required it, but because the psychological
formation required years to develop. The Compact's motto encodes three commitments
in productive tension: break the line, hold the ground, leave no fallen comrade
behind. A Knight who has resolved the tension between advance, defense, and
recovery in a coherent personal doctrine has completed the most important part of
their formation.

@@yThe Academies@@N
The transition from Compact-era mentorship to formal Knight academies happened
through the Ash-and-Iron Decades as Midgaard's militarization demanded standardized
officer training. Academies formalized what had been individually transmitted:
written curricula, standardized assessment, and institutional memory persisting
across generations. Academy training produces practitioners capable of applying
Knight doctrine in any tactical context, trading the deep contextual specialization
of Compact-era practitioners for adaptability and reliable quantity.

@@yThe Seven Shade Arches@@N
Knight doctrine acknowledges a debt to Warden-Sergeant Caleph Dunmar's engagement
at the Seven Shade Arches. His forty-three-day siege defense demonstrated how
formation discipline creates force multiplication: a small number of practitioners
operating as a coherent defensive system effectively resisted a much larger force
that could not match their coordination. The engagement remains a cornerstone of
academy curriculum.
